<div id="review_22180340" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/22180340" />
    <a title="carrietracy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/87425-carrietracy"><img alt="carrietracy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1262135805p2/87425.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/22180340?book_show_action=true">May 13, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="carrietracy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="carrietracy" href="/user/show/87425-carrietracy">carrietracy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/87425-carrietracy?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/87425-carrietracy?shelf=abandoned">abandoned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/87425-carrietracy?shelf=yum">yum</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer22180340" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12301958560044344601">I really wanted to read this book, I wanted to finish this book, but it felt like work. It is relentless in its insistence on mentioning the name of anyone ever connected to the culinary scene in America. I&apos;m relatively familiar with most of the people mentioned, but I can&apos;t say I was made to care. There were gems of information in the book that made it worth the slogging, I was fascinated by Jacques Pepin&apos;s association with Howard Johnson&apos;s, and the shipping of mushrooms from Oregon to Germany </span>
  <span id="freeText12301958560044344601" style="display:none">I really wanted to read this book, I wanted to finish this book, but it felt like work. It is relentless in its insistence on mentioning the name of anyone ever connected to the culinary scene in America. I'm relatively familiar with most of the people mentioned, but I can't say I was made to care. There were gems of information in the book that made it worth the slogging, I was fascinated by Jacques Pepin's association with Howard Johnson's, and the shipping of mushrooms from Oregon to Germany for canning and then being returned to the US where they couldn't get fresh mushrooms, but it just wasn't worth it. I shouldn't dread sitting down to read, it shouldn't be homework, and it felt like it was. I recommend it only for the most dedicated foodies or people with a strong knowledge of the American culinary scene who want to follow all the name-dropping.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12301958560044344601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


