<span id="freeTextContainer1631860829161024774">I feel that this book is not what it claims to be. It&apos;s really a history of gourmet chefs and NY Times food reviewers, with almost no social context. It&apos;s as if someone just said, &quot;Hey, why don&apos;t I make cheese out of goat&apos;s milk?!&quot; I wanted it to be more about trends in ordinary people&apos;s eating habits, to explain how my own finickiness (like only buying bakery bread and not long sleeves of square loaves) fits into a social (and economic?) pattern. I wondered if I&apos;d misinterpreted the blurb, but </span>
  <span id="freeText1631860829161024774" style="display:none">I feel that this book is not what it claims to be. It's really a history of gourmet chefs and NY Times food reviewers, with almost no social context. It's as if someone just said, "Hey, why don't I make cheese out of goat's milk?!" I wanted it to be more about trends in ordinary people's eating habits, to explain how my own finickiness (like only buying bakery bread and not long sleeves of square loaves) fits into a social (and economic?) pattern. I wondered if I'd misinterpreted the blurb, but if I did it was only a matter of degree.</span>
